# Project: Jest JavaScript Unit Test Framework

## Framework Structure
- Use Jest as the primary test runner for JavaScript and TypeScript projects
- Organize tests in __tests__ directories or alongside source files with .test.js/.spec.js extensions
- Use TypeScript with @types/jest or Jest's built-in type support (jest-circus)
- Configure jest.config.js (or jest.config.ts) at the project root

## Coding Standards
- Follow JavaScript/TypeScript best practices
- Use meaningful describe and test/it block names that read as sentences
- Implement clean code principles and single responsibility in tests
- Limit describe block nesting to 3 levels maximum

## Test Organization
- Group related tests using describe blocks
- Use it/test functions for individual test cases
- Implement beforeEach/afterEach and beforeAll/afterAll for setup and teardown
- Separate unit, integration, and snapshot tests into distinct directories

## Best Practices
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert (AAA) pattern
- Write focused, single-responsibility tests
- Avoid shared mutable state between tests
- Use jest.fn() for creating mock functions
- Use jest.spyOn() for spying on existing methods without replacing them
- Clear or restore mocks with jest.clearAllMocks() or jest.restoreAllMocks() in afterEach

## Mocking Strategies
- Use jest.mock() for automatic module mocking at the top of test files
- Use manual mocks in __mocks__ directories for complex dependencies
- Use jest.useFakeTimers() for testing time-dependent logic
- Mock HTTP requests with msw (Mock Service Worker) or jest-mock-axios
- Use jest.isolateModules() to reset module registry for tests requiring fresh imports

## Assertions
- Use expect() with descriptive matchers (toBe, toEqual, toStrictEqual, toContain)
- Use .not for negative assertions
- Use toMatchSnapshot() for stable output regression testing
- Prefer toEqual over toBe for object and array comparisons
- Use toThrow / toThrowError for error assertion

## Coverage
- Configure coverage collection via collectCoverage: true or --coverage flag
- Use coverageProvider: 'v8' for performance or 'babel' for accuracy
- Set meaningful thresholds in coverageThreshold (statements, branches, functions, lines)
- Use collectCoverageFrom to target specific files and exclude generated code
- Generate HTML and LCOV reports for visualization and CI integration

## Performance
- Use --runInBand for serial execution when debugging or avoiding port conflicts
- Use --testPathPattern or --testNamePattern to run focused test subsets
- Enable test caching (default) to skip unchanged test files
- Configure maxWorkers to balance CPU usage and parallel execution speed

## Snapshot Testing
- Keep snapshots small and focused on stable UI output
- Update snapshots intentionally with --updateSnapshot (-u) flag
- Store snapshots in __snapshots__ directories co-located with test files
- Review snapshot diffs carefully in code review to catch unintended changes

## Test Data Management
- Use factory functions or fixtures for reusable, consistent test data
- Define TypeScript types/interfaces for all test data structures
- Avoid hardcoded magic values; use named constants
- Use @faker-js/faker for realistic, dynamic test data generation

## CI/CD Integration
- Use --ci flag in CI environments to fail on missing snapshots
- Configure reporters: use 'default' locally, 'jest-junit' for CI pipelines
- Cache node_modules and Jest's cache directory (.jest-cache) between CI runs
- Upload coverage to Codecov, SonarQube, or similar services

## Environment Configuration
- Use testEnvironment: 'node' for backend tests and 'jsdom' for frontend/DOM tests
- Set globals via setupFilesAfterFramework for global test utilities
- Use .env.test files with dotenv for environment-specific configuration
- Configure moduleNameMapper for path aliases and static asset mocks

## Error Handling
- Test both happy paths and error/edge cases
- Assert on specific error messages and error types
- Use expect(fn).toThrow(ErrorType) for synchronous errors
- Use await expect(promise).rejects.toThrow() for async errors

## Async Testing
- Use async/await for all asynchronous test cases
- Avoid mixing callbacks with promises in tests
- Use jest.runAllTimers() or jest.advanceTimersByTime() with fake timers
- Return promises from test functions when not using async/await

## Documentation
- Document non-obvious test setups with brief inline comments
- Maintain a __tests__/README.md for complex fixture or helper documentation
- Include examples of custom matchers in project documentation
- Document project-specific mock strategies and shared setup files

Remember to leverage Jest's watch mode (--watch or --watchAll) during development for rapid feedback, and always run the full suite before committing.
